l venues—politics, sports, film, and literature—and examine the political, cultural, material, and affective conditions that shaped celebrity in Canada and its uses both at home and abroad. The scope of the book enables the authors to highlight the trends that characterize Canadian celebrity—such as transnationality and bureaucracy—and explore the regional, linguistic, administrative, and indigenous cultures and institutions that distinguish fame in Canada from fame elsewhere. In historicizing and theorizing Canada’s complicated cultures of celebrity, Celebrity Cultures in Canada rejects the argument that nations are irrelevant in today’s global celebrityscapes or that Canada lacks a credible or adequate system for producing, distributing, and consuming celebrity. Nation and national identities continue to matter—to celebrities, to fans, and to institutions and industries that manage and profit from celebrity systems—and Canada, this collection argues, has a vibrant, powerful, and often complicated and controversial relationship to fame.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCelebrities in mass media. 0aCelebritieszCanada. 0aFamexSocial aspectszCanada. 0aFame. 0aMass media and culture. 0aMass mediaxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aPopular culturezCanada. 4aCultural Studies. 4aFilm & Media. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  aCRTC.  aCanada.  aCanadian celebrity.  aCanadian film.  aCanadian performers.  aCanadian politicians.  aCanadian popular culture.  aCanadian star system.  aCanadian television.  aIndigenous fame system.  aQuebec star system.  acelebrity.  afame in Canada.  afame.  aliterary prizes.  astars.1 aBell, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCzach, Liz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators